Finset`\n\nSince `s` is injective, the map `e ↦ (s e.1, s e.2)` is injective on `p.2.edges.toFinset`, so `(p.2.edges.map ...).toFinset.card = (p.2.edges.toFinset).card`\n\nBut `(p.2.edges.toFinset).card = (edgeSet p.2).card`.\n\n### Step 11: Actual Lean Translation\n\nTo formalize this:\n\n1. Obtain `s` from `heq`.\n2. Write `q.2 = permMapWalk n s p.2`.\n3. Show that `q.2.edges = p.2.edges.map (fun d ↦ (Sym2.mk (s d.1, s d.2)))`.\n4. Deduce that `edgeSet q.2 = (p.2.edges.map ...).toFinset`.\n5. Show that `(p.2.edges.map ...).toFinset.card = (p.2.edges.toFinset).card`.\n6. Deduce that `(edgeSet p.2).card = (edgeSet q.2).card`.\n\n### Step 12: Simplified Approach\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can directly use that:\n\n`(edgeSet p.2).card = (p.2.edges.toFinset).card`\n\nand\n\n`(edgeSet q.2).card = (q.2.edges.toFinset).card`,\n\nand then show that `(q.2.edges.toFinset).",
